{{Infobox language |name=Achagua |nativename=''Achawa'' |states=[[Colombia]] |ethnicity=[[Achagua people]] |speakers=250 |date=2000 |ref=e18 |familycolor=American |fam1=[[Maipurean languages|Arawakan]] |fam2=Northern |fam3=[[Upper Amazon Arawakan|Upper Amazon]] |fam4=Western Nawiki |fam5=Piapoko |iso3=aca |lc1=pod|ld1=Ponares? |glotto=acha1250 |glottoname=Achawa |glotto2=pona1251 |glottoname2=Ponares }}
'''Achagua''' (Achawa) is a language spoken in the [[Meta Department]] of [[Colombia]], similar to [[Piapoco language|Piapoco]]. It is estimated that 250 individuals speak the language, many of whom also speak Piapoco or [[Spanish language|Spanish]].<ref name="e18"/>
"Achagua is a language of the [[Upper Amazon Arawakan|Maipurean Arawakan]] group traditionally spoken by the Achagua people of Venezuela and east-central Colombia."<ref>{{Cite web | last = Neira | first = Alonso de | title = The Art and Vocabulary of the Achagua Language | work = World Digital Library | accessdate = 2013-05-23 | url = http://www.wdl.org/en/item/8993/ }}</ref>
A "Ponares" language is inferred from surnames, and may have been Achawa or Piapoco.
There is 1 to 5% literacy in Achagua.<ref name="e18"/>
