The '''Bohemian Club''' ({{lang-cz|Česká beseda}}) was a [[Club (organization)|club]] founded in 1899 that was frequented by [[Chicago]]'s [[Czech American|Czech]] elite, as well as the visiting elite from [[Czechoslovakia]]. The club was used as a place to share [[Culture of the Czech Republic|Czech culture]], [[Theatre of the Czech Republic|drama]], [[Music of the Czech Republic|music]] and [[Czech literature|literature]].<ref>Frank S. Magallon, ''Chicago's Little Village'' (2010) p 37</ref>
It was visited by numerous well-known people of [[Bohemian]] descent, such as [[Anton Cermak]], [[Rudolf Friml]], [[George Halas]] and [[Otto Kerner, Jr.]].<ref>Irving Cutler, ''Chicago's Jewish West Side'' (2009) p 46</ref> It also served as host to [[Tomáš Garrigue Masaryk]], the founder and first [[List of Presidents of Czechoslovakia|President]] of [[Czechoslovakia]].<ref>Irving Cutler, ''Chicago, metropolis of the mid-continent'' (1973) p 101</ref>
