'''Seasoning''', or '''The Seasoning''', is the term applied to the [[Acclimatization|period of adjustment]] that was undertaken by African slaves and European immigrants following their first attack of [[tropical disease]], during the [[colonization]] of the [[New World|Americas]]. Malaria was the chief adversary of colonists and slaves. Death rates dramatically differed between regions in the Americas. Those who survived were known as Seasoned, and for slaves this would command a higher price.<ref>{{cite book|last=Mann|first=Charles|title=1493: How the Ecological Collision of Europe and the Americas Gave Rise to the Modern World|publisher=Granta Books|year=2011}}</ref>

